Note:
DOMAIN - Domain Name and Hostname Primitive (Tier 1)

Implements domain-name and hostname validation per RFC 1035 (Domain Names -
Implementation and Specification) and RFC 1123 (Requirements for Internet
Hosts - Application and Support). Internationalized Domain Name (IDN)
support follows RFC 3490 (IDNA: Internationalizing Domain Names in
Applications) using the Punycode encoding defined in RFC 3492.

Validation rules:
  - Total length 1..253 characters per RFC 1035 section 2.3.4
  - Each label 1..63 characters per RFC 1035 section 2.3.4
  - LDH (Letter-Digit-Hyphen) rule per RFC 1123 section 2.1:
      labels consist of ASCII letters, digits, and hyphens
      first and last characters of a label must be alphanumeric
  - Labels separated by '.'
  - Comparison is case-insensitive per RFC 1035 section 2.3.3

Punycode encoding (RFC 3492):
  Bootstring algorithm using base 36 (digits + letters) with adaptive
  bias. Provided here as the encode/decode pair operating on bare Punycode
  strings. The ToASCII / ToUnicode wrappers add the "xn--" ACE prefix and
  apply NamePrep (RFC 3491) selectively.

  This implementation correctly handles UTF-8 encoded input. For each
  Unicode code point > 127 the code point is computed from the UTF-8 byte
  sequence (1..4 bytes) and inserted into the Punycode delta stream.

NamePrep handling:
  This module performs a minimal lowercase fold per RFC 3491 section 4
  Step 1 (case mapping using ASCII tolower) which is sufficient for the
  ASCII case and the common BMP code points that are already in the
  canonical form. Full Unicode case mapping is layered on top by callers
  that link the full Unicode database.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/string_builder.runa" as SB
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/char_core.runa" as Char

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let DOMAIN_MAX_LENGTH be 253
Let LABEL_MAX_LENGTH be 63

Note: Punycode parameters per RFC 3492 section 5.
Let PUNY_BASE be 36
Let PUNY_TMIN be 1
Let PUNY_TMAX be 26
Let PUNY_SKEW be 38
Let PUNY_DAMP be 700
Let PUNY_INITIAL_BIAS be 72
Let PUNY_INITIAL_N be 128
Let PUNY_DELIMITER be 45

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CASE-INSENSITIVE LDH VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Check whether a single ASCII byte is alphanumeric per RFC 1123 section 2.1.
Helper for hostname validation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
ASCII alpha or digit.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Used to enforce label-boundary rules.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_is_alphanumeric" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ca be proc is_alpha from Char with ch
    If ca is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let cd be proc is_digit from Char with ch
    If cd is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Check whether a single ASCII byte is a valid LDH character per RFC 1123.
Letters, digits, and hyphens are valid in the middle of a label.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Alpha, digit, or '-'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Reject any character outside LDH; rejects Unicode in raw form.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_is_ldh" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ca be proc is_alpha from Char with ch
    If ca is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let cd be proc is_digit from Char with ch
    If cd is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 45:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Validate a single label per RFC 1035 + RFC 1123:
  - Length 1..63
  - All characters LDH
  - First and last characters alphanumeric (no leading/trailing hyphen)
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Length and boundary checks; loop over interior chars for LDH validity.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) over label length. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Rejects empty labels (which would create consecutive dots), labels with
non-LDH characters, and labels with leading or trailing hyphens (the
latter being reserved per RFC 5891 for ACE prefix and similar uses).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_is_valid_label" takes label as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    If label is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than LABEL_MAX_LENGTH:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let first be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with label, start
    Let first_ok be proc domain_is_alphanumeric with first
    If first_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let last_pos be start plus length minus 1
    Let last be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with label, last_pos
    Let last_ok be proc domain_is_alphanumeric with last
    If last_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 1
    Let interior_max be length minus 1
    While i is less than interior_max:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with label, start plus i
        Let ok be proc domain_is_ldh with ch
        If ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Validate a complete domain name (presentation form) per RFC 1035 and
RFC 1123. Total length must be at most 253 characters. Each dot-separated
label must satisfy the label rules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Scan for '.' separators. For each label found, validate via the label
predicate. The trailing dot of an FQDN is permitted but does not count
toward the length limit per RFC 1035 section 3.1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) over input length. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict per RFC; protects against name-injection attacks that rely on
out-of-spec characters.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_is_valid_hostname" takes domain_str as Integer returns Integer:
    If domain_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with domain_str
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let effective_length be length
    Note: Trailing dot tolerated for FQDN form.
    Let last_ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, length minus 1
    If last_ch is equal to 46:
        Set effective_length to length minus 1
    End If
    If effective_length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If effective_length is greater than DOMAIN_MAX_LENGTH:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let label_start be 0
    Let label_length be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than effective_length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, i
        If ch is equal to 46:
            Let ok be proc domain_is_valid_label with domain_str, label_start, label_length
            If ok is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Set label_start to i plus 1
            Set label_length to 0
        Otherwise:
            Set label_length to label_length plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let final_ok be proc domain_is_valid_label with domain_str, label_start, label_length
    If final_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DOMAIN MANIPULATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Return the parent domain: everything after the first label and separating
dot. For "www.example.com" returns "example.com". For "com" (no dots)
returns 0 since there is no parent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Locate first '.'; allocate substring from byte after the dot to end.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 for inputs without a parent so callers can detect the root.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_parent" takes domain_str as Integer returns Integer:
    If domain_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with domain_str
    Let i be 0
    Let dot_pos be -1
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, i
        If ch is equal to 46:
            Set dot_pos to i
            Set i to length
        Otherwise:
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While
    If dot_pos is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let parent_start be dot_pos plus 1
    Let parent_len be length minus parent_start
    If parent_len is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with domain_str, parent_start, parent_len
End Process

@Reasoning
Return the root label: the rightmost label after the final dot. For
"www.example.com" returns "com". For "localhost" (no dots) returns a copy
of the whole string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Locate last '.'; copy from byte after that dot to end. If no dot, copy
the entire input.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No external input handling beyond what is documented.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_root" takes domain_str as Integer returns Integer:
    If domain_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with domain_str
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be length minus 1
    Let last_dot be -1
    Let done be 0
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        If done is equal to 0:
            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, i
            If ch is equal to 46:
                Set last_dot to i
                Set done to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set i to i minus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set i to -1
        End If
    End While
    If last_dot is less than 0:
        Return proc string_duplicate from StringPrim with domain_str
    End If
    Let root_start be last_dot plus 1
    Let root_len be length minus root_start
    Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with domain_str, root_start, root_len
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PUNYCODE HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Convert a Punycode digit value 0..35 to its ASCII character per RFC 3492
section 5. Digits 0..25 map to 'a'..'z'; digits 26..35 map to '0'..'9'.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Range branch.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on out-of-range input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_puny_digit_to_char" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is less than 26:
        Return value plus 97
    End If
    If value is less than 36:
        Return value minus 26 plus 48
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

@Reasoning
Convert an ASCII Punycode character to its digit value 0..35 per RFC 3492.
'a'..'z' / 'A'..'Z' -> 0..25; '0'..'9' -> 26..35.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Range tests on the three character classes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on invalid character.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_puny_char_to_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return ch minus 97
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return ch minus 65
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return ch plus 26 minus 48
        End If
    End If
    Return -1
End Process

@Reasoning
Compute the threshold value t per RFC 3492 section 6.1 step 3.6 used by
the variable-length integer encoding/decoding loops. The threshold is
TMIN if k <= bias + TMIN, TMAX if k >= bias + TMAX, or k - bias otherwise.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Straightforward branch over the bias-relative position.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No external input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_puny_threshold" takes k as Integer, bias as Integer returns Integer:
    Let low_bound be bias plus PUNY_TMIN
    Let high_bound be bias plus PUNY_TMAX
    If k is less than or equal to low_bound:
        Return PUNY_TMIN
    End If
    If k is greater than or equal to high_bound:
        Return PUNY_TMAX
    End If
    Return k minus bias
End Process

@Reasoning
Adapt the bias per RFC 3492 section 6.1 step 3.5 / section 3.4. Called
after each code-point insertion to update the encoding bias for the next
delta.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Standard adaptation: divide delta by DAMP on first delta else by 2, add
delta / numpoints, then loop dividing while delta exceeds the threshold,
incrementing k by BASE each iteration. Finally k + (BASE - TMIN + 1) *
delta / (delta + SKEW).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(log delta).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No external input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_puny_adapt" takes delta as Integer, numpoints as Integer, firsttime as Integer returns Integer:
    Let d be delta
    If firsttime is equal to 1:
        Set d to d divided by PUNY_DAMP
    Otherwise:
        Set d to d divided by 2
    End If
    Set d to d plus (d divided by numpoints)
    Let k be 0
    Let limit be ((PUNY_BASE minus PUNY_TMIN) multiplied by PUNY_TMAX) divided by 2
    While d is greater than limit:
        Set d to d divided by (PUNY_BASE minus PUNY_TMIN)
        Set k to k plus PUNY_BASE
    End While
    Let bias be k plus (((PUNY_BASE minus PUNY_TMIN plus 1) multiplied by d) divided by (d plus PUNY_SKEW))
    Return bias
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: UTF-8 DECODE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Decode a UTF-8 byte sequence into a sequence of Unicode code points.
Returns an allocated array of int64 code points plus the count via two
out-parameter pointers. Used by the Punycode encoder which operates on
code points, not bytes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walk the UTF-8 byte stream. For each lead byte determine the sequence
length from the high bits and combine the trailing 6-bit groups. Reject
malformed sequences (returns 0).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) over input bytes. Space: O(n) for the code-point buffer in
the worst case.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict UTF-8: rejects overlong encodings, lone surrogates, and bytes
outside the legal lead-trail patterns.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_utf8_decode" takes bytes_ptr as Integer, byte_length as Integer, out_count_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If bytes_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If byte_length is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let buffer_capacity be byte_length plus 1
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_capacity multiplied by 8
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    Let cp_count be 0
    Let parse_failed be 0
    While i is less than byte_length:
        If parse_failed is equal to 0:
            Let b0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with bytes_ptr, i
            If b0 is less than 128:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer, cp_count multiplied by 8, b0
                Set cp_count to cp_count plus 1
                Set i to i plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If b0 is less than 192:
                    Note: continuation byte at lead position - invalid.
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                Otherwise:
                    If b0 is less than 224:
                        Note: 2-byte sequence.
                        If i plus 1 is greater than or equal to byte_length:
                            Set parse_failed to 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with bytes_ptr, i plus 1
                            If b1 is less than 128:
                                Set parse_failed to 1
                            End If
                            If b1 is greater than or equal to 192:
                                Set parse_failed to 1
                            End If
                            If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                                Let cp be ((b0 minus 192) multiplied by 64) plus (b1 minus 128)
                                If cp is less than 128:
                                    Set parse_failed to 1
                                End If
                                If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer, cp_count multiplied by 8, cp
                                    Set cp_count to cp_count plus 1
                                    Set i to i plus 2
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        If b0 is less than 240:
                            Note: 3-byte sequence.
                            If i plus 2 is greater than or equal to byte_length:
                                Set parse_failed to 1
                            Otherwise:
                                Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with bytes_ptr, i plus 1
                                Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with bytes_ptr, i plus 2
                                If b1 is less than 128:
                                    Set parse_failed to 1
                                End If
                                If b1 is greater than or equal to 192:
                                    Set parse_failed to 1
                                End If
                                If b2 is less than 128:
                                    Set parse_failed to 1
                                End If
                                If b2 is greater than or equal to 192:
                                    Set parse_failed to 1
                                End If
                                If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                                    Let cp be ((b0 minus 224) multiplied by 4096) plus ((b1 minus 128) multiplied by 64) plus (b2 minus 128)
                                    If cp is less than 2048:
                                        Set parse_failed to 1
                                    End If
                                    Note: Reject surrogates 0xD800..0xDFFF.
                                    If cp is greater than or equal to 55296:
                                        If cp is less than or equal to 57343:
                                            Set parse_failed to 1
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                    If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer, cp_count multiplied by 8, cp
                                        Set cp_count to cp_count plus 1
                                        Set i to i plus 3
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        Otherwise:
                            If b0 is less than 248:
                                Note: 4-byte sequence.
                                If i plus 3 is greater than or equal to byte_length:
                                    Set parse_failed to 1
                                Otherwise:
                                    Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with bytes_ptr, i plus 1
                                    Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with bytes_ptr, i plus 2
                                    Let b3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with bytes_ptr, i plus 3
                                    If b1 is less than 128:
                                        Set parse_failed to 1
                                    End If
                                    If b1 is greater than or equal to 192:
                                        Set parse_failed to 1
                                    End If
                                    If b2 is less than 128:
                                        Set parse_failed to 1
                                    End If
                                    If b2 is greater than or equal to 192:
                                        Set parse_failed to 1
                                    End If
                                    If b3 is less than 128:
                                        Set parse_failed to 1
                                    End If
                                    If b3 is greater than or equal to 192:
                                        Set parse_failed to 1
                                    End If
                                    If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                                        Let cp be ((b0 minus 240) multiplied by 262144) plus ((b1 minus 128) multiplied by 4096) plus ((b2 minus 128) multiplied by 64) plus (b3 minus 128)
                                        If cp is less than 65536:
                                            Set parse_failed to 1
                                        End If
                                        If cp is greater than 1114111:
                                            Set parse_failed to 1
                                        End If
                                        If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                                            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with buffer, cp_count multiplied by 8, cp
                                            Set cp_count to cp_count plus 1
                                            Set i to i plus 4
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            Otherwise:
                                Set parse_failed to 1
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set i to byte_length
        End If
    End While
    If parse_failed is equal to 1:
        proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
        Return 0
    End If
    If out_count_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with out_count_ptr, 0, cp_count
    End If
    Return buffer
End Process

@Reasoning
Encode a single Unicode code point into a UTF-8 byte sequence in the
provided StringBuilder. Used by the Punycode decoder to emit decoded
output as UTF-8.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Standard UTF-8 encoding per RFC 3629:
  cp < 128         -> 1 byte
  cp < 2048        -> 2 bytes 110xxxxx 10xxxxxx
  cp < 65536       -> 3 bytes 1110xxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
  cp < 1114112     -> 4 bytes 11110xxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Rejects surrogates and out-of-range code points.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_utf8_encode" takes sb as Integer, cp as Integer returns Integer:
    If sb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is greater than 1114111:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cp is greater than or equal to 55296:
        If cp is less than or equal to 57343:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    If cp is less than 128:
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, cp
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is less than 2048:
        Let b0 be 192 plus (cp divided by 64)
        Let b1 be 128 plus (cp modulo by 64)
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b0
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b1
        Return 1
    End If
    If cp is less than 65536:
        Let b0 be 224 plus (cp divided by 4096)
        Let b1 be 128 plus ((cp divided by 64) modulo by 64)
        Let b2 be 128 plus (cp modulo by 64)
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b0
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b1
        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b2
        Return 1
    End If
    Let b0 be 240 plus (cp divided by 262144)
    Let b1 be 128 plus ((cp divided by 4096) modulo by 64)
    Let b2 be 128 plus ((cp divided by 64) modulo by 64)
    Let b3 be 128 plus (cp modulo by 64)
    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b0
    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b1
    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b2
    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, b3
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PUNYCODE ENCODE / DECODE (RFC 3492)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Encode a Unicode label to Punycode per RFC 3492 section 6.3 (encoding).
Accepts a UTF-8 input string and produces an ASCII Punycode string
suitable for ACE prefixing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Decode UTF-8 input into a code-point array.
2. Copy all basic (< 128) code points to the output, in order, followed
   by the delimiter '-' if any basic code points were copied.
3. Initialize n = 128, delta = 0, bias = 72.
4. Repeat while there are non-basic code points to emit:
   a. Find the smallest code point m >= n in the input.
   b. delta += (m - n) * (h + 1).
   c. n = m.
   d. For each code point c in the input in order:
        If c < n, delta++.
        If c == n: emit a variable-length integer for delta using base 36
                   with adaptive bias; reset delta; update bias.
   e. delta++; n++.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n^2) over code-point count. Space: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on UTF-8 decoding failure or allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_punycode_encode" takes utf8_input as Integer returns Integer:
    If utf8_input is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let input_len be proc string_length from StringCore with utf8_input
    Let count_holder be proc allocate from Layout with 8
    If count_holder is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with count_holder, 0, 0
    Let codepoints be proc domain_utf8_decode with utf8_input, input_len, count_holder
    If codepoints is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with count_holder
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cp_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with count_holder, 0
    proc deallocate from Layout with count_holder

    Let sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If sb is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with codepoints
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1 - emit basic code points.
    Let h be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than cp_count:
        Let cp be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with codepoints, i multiplied by 8
        If cp is less than 128:
            proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, cp
            Set h to h plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let b be h
    If b is greater than 0:
        If b is less than cp_count:
            proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, PUNY_DELIMITER
        End If
    End If

    Let n be PUNY_INITIAL_N
    Let delta be 0
    Let bias be PUNY_INITIAL_BIAS
    Let total_cp be cp_count

    While h is less than total_cp:
        Note: Find minimum code point m >= n.
        Let m be 2147483647
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than total_cp:
            Let cp be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with codepoints, i multiplied by 8
            If cp is greater than or equal to n:
                If cp is less than m:
                    Set m to cp
                End If
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set delta to delta plus ((m minus n) multiplied by (h plus 1))
        Set n to m

        Set i to 0
        While i is less than total_cp:
            Let cp be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with codepoints, i multiplied by 8
            If cp is less than n:
                Set delta to delta plus 1
            End If
            If cp is equal to n:
                Note: Variable-length integer emit.
                Let q be delta
                Let k be PUNY_BASE
                Let inner_done be 0
                While inner_done is equal to 0:
                    Let t be proc domain_puny_threshold with k, bias
                    If q is less than t:
                        Let dch be proc domain_puny_digit_to_char with q
                        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, dch
                        Set inner_done to 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Let digit_val be t plus ((q minus t) modulo by (PUNY_BASE minus t))
                        Let dch be proc domain_puny_digit_to_char with digit_val
                        proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, dch
                        Set q to (q minus t) divided by (PUNY_BASE minus t)
                        Set k to k plus PUNY_BASE
                    End If
                End While
                Let first_flag be 0
                If h is equal to b:
                    Set first_flag to 1
                End If
                Set bias to proc domain_puny_adapt with delta, h plus 1, first_flag
                Set delta to 0
                Set h to h plus 1
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Set delta to delta plus 1
        Set n to n plus 1
    End While

    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with sb
    proc deallocate from Layout with codepoints
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Decode a Punycode-encoded ASCII label to UTF-8 per RFC 3492 section 6.2.
The input is the bare Punycode (without "xn--" prefix).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Locate the last '-' (delimiter). Everything before it is the basic
   code-point prefix; copy directly into the code-point buffer.
2. Initialize n = 128, i = 0, bias = 72, output index = number of basic
   code points.
3. While input remains:
   a. Decode a variable-length integer into 'delta' using base-36 digits
      and threshold(k, bias).
   b. i += delta.
   c. n += i / (out_len + 1); i = i modulo (out_len + 1).
   d. Insert code point n at position i in the output buffer.
   e. bias = adapt(delta, out_len + 1, first_flag); i += 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n^2). Space: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict: rejects out-of-range digits, integer overflow during delta
accumulation, and missing trailing data.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_punycode_decode" takes puny_input as Integer returns Integer:
    If puny_input is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let input_len be proc string_length from StringCore with puny_input
    Note: Find last delimiter '-' in input.
    Let delim_pos be -1
    Let i be input_len minus 1
    Let scanning be 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        If scanning is equal to 1:
            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with puny_input, i
            If ch is equal to PUNY_DELIMITER:
                Set delim_pos to i
                Set scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                Set i to i minus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set i to -1
        End If
    End While

    Note: Allocate code-point buffer big enough for worst case.
    Let cap be input_len plus 1
    Let codepoints be proc allocate from Layout with cap multiplied by 8
    If codepoints is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let out_len be 0
    If delim_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
        Note: Copy basic prefix. Reject any non-ASCII byte (basic code points must be < 128).
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than delim_pos:
            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with puny_input, k
            If ch is greater than or equal to 128:
                proc deallocate from Layout with codepoints
                Return 0
            End If
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with codepoints, out_len multiplied by 8, ch
            Set out_len to out_len plus 1
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let parse_pos be 0
    If delim_pos is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set parse_pos to delim_pos plus 1
    End If
    Let n be PUNY_INITIAL_N
    Let bias be PUNY_INITIAL_BIAS
    Let ip be 0
    Let parse_failed be 0

    While parse_pos is less than input_len:
        If parse_failed is equal to 0:
            Let old_i be ip
            Let w be 1
            Let k be PUNY_BASE
            Let inner_done be 0
            While inner_done is equal to 0:
                If parse_pos is greater than or equal to input_len:
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                    Set inner_done to 1
                Otherwise:
                    Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with puny_input, parse_pos
                    Let digit be proc domain_puny_char_to_digit with ch
                    Set parse_pos to parse_pos plus 1
                    If digit is less than 0:
                        Set parse_failed to 1
                        Set inner_done to 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Set ip to ip plus (digit multiplied by w)
                        Let t be proc domain_puny_threshold with k, bias
                        If digit is less than t:
                            Set inner_done to 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Set w to w multiplied by (PUNY_BASE minus t)
                            Set k to k plus PUNY_BASE
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While
            If parse_failed is equal to 0:
                Let out_plus_one be out_len plus 1
                Let first_flag be 0
                If old_i is equal to 0:
                    Set first_flag to 1
                End If
                Set bias to proc domain_puny_adapt with ip minus old_i, out_plus_one, first_flag
                Set n to n plus (ip divided by out_plus_one)
                Set ip to ip modulo by out_plus_one
                Note: Shift code points right by 1 starting at ip to make room.
                Let shift_pos be out_len
                While shift_pos is greater than ip:
                    Let val be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with codepoints, (shift_pos minus 1) multiplied by 8
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with codepoints, shift_pos multiplied by 8, val
                    Set shift_pos to shift_pos minus 1
                End While
                proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with codepoints, ip multiplied by 8, n
                Set out_len to out_len plus 1
                Set ip to ip plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set parse_pos to input_len
        End If
    End While

    If parse_failed is equal to 1:
        proc deallocate from Layout with codepoints
        Return 0
    End If

    Let sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If sb is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with codepoints
        Return 0
    End If
    Let q be 0
    While q is less than out_len:
        Let cp be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with codepoints, q multiplied by 8
        proc domain_utf8_encode with sb, cp
        Set q to q plus 1
    End While
    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with sb
    proc deallocate from Layout with codepoints
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOASCII / TOUNICODE PER RFC 3490
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Test whether a label contains any non-ASCII byte. Used to decide whether
ToASCII must invoke Punycode for the label.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear scan checking byte > 127.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No external input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_label_has_non_ascii" takes label as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    If label is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with label, start plus i
        If ch is greater than 127:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Convert a Unicode domain name (UTF-8) to its ASCII Compatible Encoding
(ACE) form per RFC 3490 (ToASCII). Each label containing non-ASCII bytes
is Punycode-encoded and prefixed with "xn--".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Split on '.', process each label, join with '.'. Labels with non-ASCII
content are passed through domain_punycode_encode and prefixed with
"xn--". ASCII-only labels are emitted verbatim (lowercased for
case-insensitive equivalence per RFC 3491 section 4 step 1 basic case).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) plus the Punycode cost per non-ASCII label.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict: rejects malformed UTF-8 in any label, and rejects labels whose
encoded form exceeds the 63-byte limit per RFC 1035.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_to_ascii" takes utf8_input as Integer returns Integer:
    If utf8_input is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with utf8_input
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let out_sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If out_sb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let label_start be 0
    Let i be 0
    Let parse_failed be 0
    While i is less than length plus 1:
        If parse_failed is equal to 0:
            Let at_end be 0
            If i is equal to length:
                Set at_end to 1
            End If
            Let is_dot be 0
            If at_end is equal to 0:
                Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with utf8_input, i
                If ch is equal to 46:
                    Set is_dot to 1
                End If
            End If
            If at_end is equal to 1:
                Set is_dot to 1
            End If
            If is_dot is equal to 1:
                Let label_length be i minus label_start
                If label_length is greater than 0:
                    Let has_non_ascii be proc domain_label_has_non_ascii with utf8_input, label_start, label_length
                    If has_non_ascii is equal to 1:
                        Let label_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with utf8_input, label_start, label_length
                        If label_str is equal to 0:
                            Set parse_failed to 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Let encoded be proc domain_punycode_encode with label_str
                            proc deallocate from Layout with label_str
                            If encoded is equal to 0:
                                Set parse_failed to 1
                            Otherwise:
                                Let encoded_len be proc string_length from StringCore with encoded
                                If encoded_len plus 4 is greater than LABEL_MAX_LENGTH:
                                    proc deallocate from Layout with encoded
                                    Set parse_failed to 1
                                Otherwise:
                                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, 120
                                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, 110
                                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, 45
                                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, 45
                                    proc stringbuilder_append from SB with out_sb, encoded
                                    proc deallocate from Layout with encoded
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: ASCII-only label, lowercase fold.
                        Let k be 0
                        While k is less than label_length:
                            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with utf8_input, label_start plus k
                            Let lc be proc to_lower from Char with ch
                            proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, lc
                            Set k to k plus 1
                        End While
                    End If
                End If
                If at_end is equal to 0:
                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, 46
                End If
                Set label_start to i plus 1
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set i to length plus 1
        End If
    End While
    If parse_failed is equal to 1:
        proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with out_sb
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with out_sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with out_sb
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Convert an ASCII Compatible Encoding (ACE) domain name to its Unicode
(UTF-8) form per RFC 3490 (ToUnicode). Each "xn--<puny>" label is
Punycode-decoded; other labels are passed through unchanged.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Split on '.', process each label, join with '.'. Labels beginning with
"xn--" are passed through domain_punycode_decode (after stripping the
prefix). Non-ACE labels are emitted as-is.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) plus the Punycode-decode cost per ACE label.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Decoder rejects malformed Punycode but tolerates non-ACE labels.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "domain_to_unicode" takes ace_input as Integer returns Integer:
    If ace_input is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with ace_input
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let out_sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If out_sb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let label_start be 0
    Let i be 0
    Let parse_failed be 0
    While i is less than length plus 1:
        If parse_failed is equal to 0:
            Let at_end be 0
            If i is equal to length:
                Set at_end to 1
            End If
            Let is_dot be 0
            If at_end is equal to 0:
                Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ace_input, i
                If ch is equal to 46:
                    Set is_dot to 1
                End If
            End If
            If at_end is equal to 1:
                Set is_dot to 1
            End If
            If is_dot is equal to 1:
                Let label_length be i minus label_start
                If label_length is greater than 0:
                    Let is_ace be 0
                    If label_length is greater than 4:
                        Let c0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ace_input, label_start
                        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ace_input, label_start plus 1
                        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ace_input, label_start plus 2
                        Let c3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ace_input, label_start plus 3
                        Let lc0 be proc to_lower from Char with c0
                        Let lc1 be proc to_lower from Char with c1
                        If lc0 is equal to 120:
                            If lc1 is equal to 110:
                                If c2 is equal to 45:
                                    If c3 is equal to 45:
                                        Set is_ace to 1
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    If is_ace is equal to 1:
                        Let puny_start be label_start plus 4
                        Let puny_len be label_length minus 4
                        Let puny_str be proc string_substring from StringPrim with ace_input, puny_start, puny_len
                        If puny_str is equal to 0:
                            Set parse_failed to 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Let decoded be proc domain_punycode_decode with puny_str
                            proc deallocate from Layout with puny_str
                            If decoded is equal to 0:
                                Set parse_failed to 1
                            Otherwise:
                                proc stringbuilder_append from SB with out_sb, decoded
                                proc deallocate from Layout with decoded
                            End If
                        End If
                    Otherwise:
                        Let k be 0
                        While k is less than label_length:
                            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ace_input, label_start plus k
                            proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, ch
                            Set k to k plus 1
                        End While
                    End If
                End If
                If at_end is equal to 0:
                    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with out_sb, 46
                End If
                Set label_start to i plus 1
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set i to length plus 1
        End If
    End While
    If parse_failed is equal to 1:
        proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with out_sb
        Return 0
    End If
    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with out_sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with out_sb
    Return result
End Process
